  "prompt": "What are some popular myths about muscle?",
  "response": "Here are some popular myths about muscle:\n\n1. Muscle Myth: Lifting weights makes women bulky\n\u2022 Truth: Women typically lack enough testosterone to build large muscles easily\n\n2. Myth: Muscle turns into fat when you stop exercising\n\u2022 Truth: Muscle and fat are different tissues; muscle can shrink, but doesn't \"turn into\" fat\n\n3. Myth: You can spot reduce fat from specific body areas\n\u2022 Truth: Fat loss occurs overall, not from targeted areas\n\n4. Myth: Muscle weighs more than fat\n\u2022 Truth: A pound of muscle and a pound of fat weigh the same; muscle is denser\n\n5. Myth: No pain, no gain\n\u2022 Truth: Muscle growth doesn't require extreme pain or constant soreness\n\n6. Myth: You must work out every day\n\u2022 Truth: Rest and recovery are crucial for muscle growth and preventing injury\n\n7. Myth: Protein supplements are necessary for muscle growth\n\u2022 Truth: Most people can get sufficient protein from diet alone\n\n8. Myth: Lifting heavy weights is the only way to build muscle\n\u2022 Truth: Various resistance training methods can build muscle effectively\n\n9. Myth: Muscles become less responsive to training over time\n\u2022 Truth: Muscles can continue to grow with proper nutrition and varied training\n\nThese myths often persist despite scientific evidence to the contrary.",
